6.25pm A superb effort from Chandimal carries Sri Lanka to 226, a score they will take after that middle-overs stutter. Batting in his final ODI, Dilshan got Sri Lanka off to a solid start but picked out midwicket for 42. Sri Lanka kept losing wickets through the middle, setting them back, but Chandimal ensured he stayed there till the end to give some respectability to the score. Could be quite a tricky chase actually. Stick around to find out.

2.29pm Sri Lanka give Dilshan a guard of honour as he comes out, gets a hug from Mathews and waits for his partner. He walks out to bat for the last time in ODI cricket. A punch of gloves with Gunathilaka, a handshake with Warner. Mitch Starc has the ball. A couple of slips in place. Australia need a good start. Here we go.

2.10pm Andrew Fernando tells me it is a sold out game. "Traffic's backed up quite a way near the entrance, so the ground should fill shortly. Very warm and no sign of the Dambulla wind just yet," he adds.

2.00pm Sri Lanka won the toss and chose to bat. A few changes for Australia. Marsh comes in for Smith, Hastings in for Henriques, Hazlewood back for Lyon.

Angelo Mathews: "The wicket looks dry again, we 'd like to put the runs on the board and defend it. All our emotions are on, Dilshan has been a wonderful servant for SL cricket."

David Warner: "We'd have batted as well. Three changes. He's (Smith) going to be missed, looks a nice wicket. Nice and dry again.

Sri Lanka: Gunathilaka, Dilshan, K Mendis, Chandimal, Mathews, K Perera, Dhananjaya de Silva, T Perera, D Perera, Prasanna, Aponso.

1.50pm A beautiful day in Dambulla, hosting day-night cricket for the first time in six years. Bad weather is NOT expected to intervene, great news because this a massive game in the context of the series. Don't see either side wanting to bowl first with the surface expected to get harder to score runs on. Toss not far away.

1.40pm Here is a little bit on Dilshan from Andrew Fernando: his contributions to SL cricket, Dilshan's best and his ODI numbers from Shiva Jayaraman.

1.30pm Four days ago, Sri Lanka levelled the five-match series 1-1 with a resounding display in Colombo . Since then, it seems the face of the series has changed altogether. Soo much has happened, none bigger than Tillakaratne Dilshan announcing this will be his last ODI, putting to an end a career that has spanned 329 games and 10248 runs. He needs 158 runs or more to overtake Brian Lara and move to 10th on the highest run-getters in ODI cricket.

Also, captain Steven Smith will play no further part in the series after he was rested for the South Africa series. This is what Sri Lanka captain Angelo Mathews had to say: "Honestly, if it was me, I wouldn't have [left], because it's a tough tour," Mathews said. "You need the captain alongside the playing XI." As a result, David Warner will lead the Australia side in their bid for an ODI series win.
